# Incident Response Runbook: Database Outage

## Severity Classification

| Severity | Definition | Response Time |
| :---: | --- | ---: |
| P1 | Complete service outage | 5 min |
| P2 | Degraded performance for all users | 15 min |
| P3 | Partial outage affecting some users | 30 min |
| P4 | Minor issue, no user impact | 4 hours |

## Immediate Actions

!> If the database is completely unresponsive, escalate to P1 immediately.

1. Verify the outage is real (not a monitoring false positive)
2. Check the database status dashboard
3. Notify the on-call DBA

```bash
# Check database connectivity
pg_isready -h db.internal.example.com -p 5432

# Check replication lag
psql -c "SELECT now() - pg_last_xact_replay_timestamp() AS lag;"
```

## Diagnosis

### Connection Pool Exhaustion

```bash
# Check active connections
psql -c "SELECT count(*) FROM pg_stat_activity;"

# Find long-running queries
psql -c "SELECT pid, now() - pg_stat_activity.query_start AS duration, query
FROM pg_stat_activity
WHERE state != 'idle'
ORDER BY duration DESC
LIMIT 10;"
```

W> Do not kill connections without understanding which service owns them.

### Disk Space

```bash
# Check disk usage
df -h /var/lib/postgresql/

# Find large tables
psql -c "SELECT relname, pg_size_pretty(pg_total_relation_size(relid))
FROM pg_catalog.pg_statio_user_tables
ORDER BY pg_total_relation_size(relid) DESC
LIMIT 10;"
```

### Replication Issues

```bash
# Check replication status
psql -c "SELECT * FROM pg_stat_replication;"
```

## Recovery Steps

- [x] Verify the issue
- [ ] Identify root cause
- [ ] Apply fix
- [ ] Verify recovery
- [ ] Update status page
- [ ] Write post-mortem

X> Restoring from backup is a last resort. It results in data loss since the last backup.

## Post-Incident

N> A post-mortem document must be completed within 48 hours of incident resolution.

T> Use the post-mortem template at `docs/templates/post-mortem.md`.
